        {
            "slide_number": 9,
            "title": "Semi-Markov Decision Processes",
            "elements": [
                {
                    "id": "slide_9_shape_0",
                    "type": "text_box",
                    "text": "Semi-Markov Decision Processes",
                    "position": {
                        "x": 144.0,
                        "y": 72.0,
                        "width": 1008.0,
                        "height": 156.0
                    },
                    "style": {
                        "font_size": null,
                        "bold": false,
                        "italic": false,
                        "color": null,
                        "background_color": null
                    },
                    "metadata": {
                        "bullet_hierarchy": [
                            {
                                "level": 0,
                                "text": "Semi-Markov Decision Processes"
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                },
                {
                    "id": "slide_9_shape_1",
                    "type": "text_box",
                    "text": "It is a semi-MDP because the process is Markovian at the level of decision points/epochs (at the level of the decisions over options) but not at the \"flat\" level. That is, if you don't observe the current choice of options along the trajectories and only see state-action pairs, that process won't be Markovian.\n\nSemi-MDPs are thus used to deal with such problems that involve actions of different levels of abstraction. Hierarchical reinforcement learning (HRL) is a generalization (or extension) of reinforcement learning where the environment is modeled as a semi-MDP.",
                    "position": {
                        "x": 144.0,
                        "y": 203.73,
                        "width": 1008.0,
                        "height": 462.93
                    },
                    "style": {
                        "font_size": 25.0,
                        "bold": false,
                        "italic": false,
                        "color": "#222222",
                        "background_color": null
                    },
                    "metadata": {
                        "bullet_hierarchy": [
                            {
                                "level": 0,
                                "text": "It is a semi-MDP because the process is Markovian at the level of decision points/epochs (at the level of the decisions over options) but not at the \"flat\" level. That is, if you don't observe the current choice of options along the trajectories and only see state-action pairs, that process won't be Markovian."
                            },
                            {
                                "level": 0,
                                "text": "Semi-MDPs are thus used to deal with such problems that involve actions of different levels of abstraction. Hierarchical reinforcement learning (HRL) is a generalization (or extension) of reinforcement learning where the environment is modeled as a semi-MDP."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                }
            ],
